  <section|The background dynamics in inflation epoch>

  Friedmann equations:

  <\equation>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|H<rsup|2>=<frac|\<kappa\>|3>\<rho\>>>|<row|<cell|<wide|H|\<dot\>>=-<frac|\<kappa\>|2><wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>><rsup|2>>>|<row|<cell|<wide|\<varphi\>|\<ddot\>>+3H<wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>>+V<rprime|'>=0>>>>>
  </equation>

  where <math|\<rho\>=<frac|<wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>><rsup|2>|2>+V<around*|(|\<varphi\>|)>>.

  In the epoch of inflation, the Hubble slow roll parameters

  <\equation>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<epsilon\>=-<frac|<wide|H|\<dot\>>|H<rsup|2>>>>|<row|<cell|\<delta\>=<frac|<wide|H|\<ddot\>>|2H<wide|H|\<dot\>>>>>>>>
  </equation>

  are very small and evolve slowly:

  <\equation>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<epsilon\>\<ll\>1>>|<row|<cell|\<delta\>\<ll\>1>>|<row|<cell|<wide|\<epsilon\>|\<dot\>>\<sim\>0>>|<row|<cell|<wide|\<delta\>|\<dot\>>\<sim\>0>>>>>
  </equation>

  <strong|Note:> We consider when these requirements are satisfied and what
  can they derive out:

  First, from <math|\<epsilon\>=-<frac|<wide|H|\<dot\>>|H<rsup|2>>=<frac|3|2><frac|<wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>><rsup|2>|<around*|(|<frac|1|2><wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>><rsup|2>+V|)>>\<ll\>1>,
  we know potential dominates the density, which means the first eqn of (1)
  becomes: <math|H<rsup|2>=<frac|\<kappa\>|3>V<around*|(|\<varphi\>|)>>;

  Second, by connecting the first two eqns of (1), we can find
  <math|3H<wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>>+V<rprime|'><around*|(|\<varphi\>|)>=0>,
  from which one can get <math|<wide|\<varphi\>|\<ddot\>>\<ll\>3H<wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>>>
  by comparing with the third eqn of (1);

  Then consider back: <math|\<epsilon\>=-<frac|<wide|H|\<dot\>>|H<rsup|2>>=<frac|3|2><frac|<wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>><rsup|2>|V>=<frac|1|2\<kappa\>><around*|(|<frac|V<rprime|'>|V>|)><rsup|2>>
