  <section|The dynamics of scalar perturbations>

  <subsection|The action for scalar perturbation and its quantization>

  Scalar perturbations only have one independent field
  <math|\<cal-R\>=<frac|H|<wide|\<varphi\>|\<dot\>>>\<delta\>\<varphi\><rsup|GI>+\<Psi\>>
  or <math|v<rsub|S>=z<rsub|S> \<cal-R\>>, whose action can be derived from
  the Hilbert action plus inflation's action expanded to 2-nd order under a
  special gauge (<math|\<delta\>\<varphi\>=E=0>) by using the first order
  constraint densities:

  <\equation*>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|S<rsup|<around*|(|2|)>>>|<cell|=>|<cell|<big|int>d\<tau\>
    d<rsup|3>x<around*|(|<frac|1|2>z<rsub|S><rsup|2>\<cal-R\><rprime|'><rsup|2>-<frac|1|2>z<rsub|S><rsup|2><around*|(|\<partial\>\<cal-R\>|)><rsup|2>|)>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=>|<cell|<big|int>d\<tau\>
    d<rsup|3>x<around*|(|<frac|1|2>v<rsub|S><rprime|'><rsup|2>-<frac|1|2><around*|(|\<partial\>v<rsub|S>|)><rsup|2>+<frac|1|2><frac|z<rsub|S><rprime|''>|z<rsub|S>>v<rsub|S><rsup|2>|)>>>>>>.
  </equation*>

  When quantizing <math|\<cal-R\>> or <math|v<rsub|S>>, define
  <math|\<pi\><rsub|v<rsub|S>>=<frac|\<delta\>L|\<delta\>v<rsub|S><rprime|'>>=v<rsub|S><rprime|'>>.
  Then from <math|<around*|[|<wide|v|^><rsub|S><around*|(|x,\<tau\>|)>,<wide|\<pi\>|^><rsub|v<rsub|S>><around*|(|y,\<tau\>|)>|]>=i\<delta\><rsup|<around*|(|3|)>><around*|(|x,y|)>>
  (take <math|\<hbar\>=1=c>), we get

  <\equation>
    <around*|[|<wide|v|^><rsub|S><around*|(|x,\<tau\>|)>,<wide|v|^><rsub|S><rprime|'><around*|(|y,\<tau\>|)>|]>=i\<delta\><rsup|<around*|(|3|)>><around*|(|x,y|)>.
  </equation>

  <strong|Note:> we will choose <math|c=1=\<hbar\>> in the note, so
  <math|\<rho\><rsub|P>=m<rsub|P><rsup|4>=<frac|1|G<rsup|2>>>,
  <math|<around*|[|\<varphi\>|]>=m<rsub|P>>,
  <math|<around*|[|m|]>=m<rsub|P>>. We also use
  <math|M<rsub|P>=<around*|(|8\<pi\>G|)><rsup|-1/2>=<frac|m<rsub|P>|<sqrt|8\<pi\>>>>.

  The dynamics of <math|<wide|v|^><rsub|S>> is

  <\equation*>
    <wide|v|^><rsub|S><rprime|''>-\<Delta\><wide|v|^><rsub|S>-<frac|z<rprime|''><rsub|S>|z<rsub|S>><wide|v|^><rsub|S>=0.
  </equation*>

  <subsection|The creation and annihilation operators>

  We can expand <math|<wide|v|^><rsub|S>> as

  <\equation*>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<wide|v|^><rsub|S><around*|(|<wide|x|\<vect\>>,\<tau\>|)>>|<cell|=>|<cell|<big|int><frac|d<rsup|3>k|<around*|(|2\<pi\>|)><rsup|3/2>><wide|v|^><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>e<rsup|i<wide|k|\<vect\>>\<cdot\><wide|x|\<vect\>>>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|=>|<cell|<big|int><frac|d<rsup|3>k|<around*|(|2\<pi\>|)><rsup|3/2>><around*|[|<wide|a|^><rsub|S><around*|(|<wide|k|\<vect\>>|)>v<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>e<rsup|i<wide|k|\<vect\>>\<cdot\><wide|x|\<vect\>>>+<wide|a|^><rsup|\<dag\>><rsub|S><around*|(|<wide|k|\<vect\>>|)>v<rsup|\<ast\>><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>e<rsup|-i<wide|k|\<vect\>>\<cdot\><wide|x|\<vect\>>>|]>>>>>>
  </equation*>

  where we have used the self-adjointness of
  <math|<wide|v|^><rsub|S><around*|(|<wide|x|\<vect\>>,\<tau\>|)>> in the
  second equality, and <math|<wide|v|^><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=<wide|a|^><rsub|S><around*|(|<wide|k|\<vect\>>|)>v<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>+<wide|a|^><rsup|\<dag\>><rsub|S><around*|(|-<wide|k|\<vect\>>|)>v<rsup|\<ast\>><rsub|-<wide|k|\<vect\>>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>>.

  Then

  <\equation>
    <wide|v|^><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rprime|''>+\<omega\><rsup|2><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>
    <wide|v|^><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=0,
  </equation>

  where <math|\<omega\><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rsup|2>=k<rsup|2>-<frac|z<rsub|S><rprime|''>|z<rsub|S>>>
  is supposed to be <em|positive> <em|initially>.

  <strong|Note:>

  1. We wouldn't consider the case <math|\<omega\><rsub|k><rsup|2>\<less\>0>,
  because we can use a box-cutting such that there exists a minimum
  <math|k<rsub|m>> which makes <math|\<omega\><rsub|k<rsub|m>><rsup|2>=k<rsub|m><rsup|2>-<frac|z<rsub|S><rprime|''>|z<rsub|S>>\<gtr\>0>.
  Another reason is that we will find out the smaller <math|k> modes will
  cross out the Hubble horzion earlier than the larger ones but re-entry into
  the horzion later than the large ones, which means those negative
  <math|\<omega\><rsup|2><rsub|k>>s are still out off the horzion which needs
  not to be considered.\ 

  2. From the expression of <math|\<omega\><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rsup|2>>
  depends on the norm of <math|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>, we know that if
  <math|<wide|v|^><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>> is a solution of eqn(5), then
  <math|<wide|v|^><rsub|-<wide|k|\<vect\>>>> is too; And if
  <math|v<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>> is a solution of eqn(5), then
  <math|v<rsup|\<dag\>><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>> is too.

  We hope <math|<wide|a|^><rsub|S>> and <math|<wide|a|^><rsub|S><rsup|\<dag\>>>
  are the so-called annihilation and creation operators which have the
  property: <math|<around*|[|<wide|a|^><rsub|S><around*|(|<wide|k|\<vect\>>|)>,<wide|a|^><rsub|S><rsup|\<dag\>><around*|(|<wide|k|\<vect\>><rprime|'>|)>|]>=\<delta\><rsup|<around*|(|3|)>><around*|(|<wide|k|\<vect\>>,<wide|k|\<vect\>><rprime|'>|)>>,
  then from eqn(4) we require

  <\equation*>
    v<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>v<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rprime|'><rsup|\<ast\>>-v<rsub|-<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rsup|\<ast\>>v<rsub|-<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rprime|'>=i
  </equation*>

  which gives almost no constraint to <math|v<rsup|><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>>,
  but if we hope somemore thing: <math|v<rsub|-<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=v<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=v<rsub|k>>
  to satisfy the isotropic principle, then above relation gives the
  <em|Wronskian condition>

  <\equation>
