  <section|The dynamics of tensor perturbations>

  The calcualtions for tensor perturbations are similar to scalar
  perturbations. But there is a subtle problem related with the traceless and
  transverse conditions which are constraints. When quantizing a first class
  constraint system, one can make a gauge choice then some second class
  constraints appears and we can use the Dirac brackets to quantize it. In
  this note, we would do in this way, and address this problem in the Frouier
  space avoiding these problems, although it seems some tedious.

  <subsection|The action for tensor perturbations and its quantization>

  The tensor perturbations or gravitons are <math|D<rsub|i j>> which are
  already gauge-invariant and have the traceless and transverse conditions
  <math|D<rsub|i i>=0> and <math|\<partial\><rsub|j>D<rsub|i j>=0>. The
  action of them is derived from the Hilbert action at 2-nd order:

  <\equation>
    <label|actionoftensor>S<rsup|<around*|(|2|)>>=<frac|1|8\<kappa\>><big|int>d\<tau\><big|int>d<rsup|3>x
    a<rsup|2><around*|[|D<rprime|'><rsub|i j>D<rsub|i
    j><rprime|'>-<around*|(|\<partial\><rsub|l>D<rsub|i
    j>|)><around*|(|\<partial\><rsub|l>D<rsub|i j>|)>|]>.
  </equation>

  From the action, one also can get the dynamical eqn of
  <math|<wide|D|^><rsub|i j>>:

  <\equation>
    <label|eqnofD><wide|D|^><rprime|''><rsub|i
    j>+2\<cal-H\><wide|D|^><rprime|'><rsub|i
    j>-\<nabla\><rsup|2><wide|D|^><rsub|i j>=0.
  </equation>

  Consider the Fourier transform the perturbation fields:

  <\equation>
    <wide|D|^><rsub|i j><around*|(|x,\<tau\>|)>=<big|int><frac|d<rsup|3>k|<around*|(|2\<pi\>|)><rsup|3/2>><around*|(|<wide|D|^><rsub|i
    j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>e<rsup|i<wide|k|\<vect\>>\<cdot\><wide|x|\<vect\>>>.
  </equation>

  Because <math|<wide|D|^><rsub|i j><around*|(|x,\<tau\>|)>> is self-adjoint,
  one can find <math|<around*|(|<wide|D|^><rsub|i
  j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=<around*|(|D<rsub|i
  j>|)><rsub|-<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rsup|\<dag\>>>.

  Before we define the annihilation-creation operators, we go back to the
  classical eqns to cancel the the traceless and transverse condition.

  Note that if we make a coordinate transformation: <math|<wide|x|~>=R x>,
  where <math|R> is a constant orthogonal matrix, then
  <math|D<around*|(|x,\<tau\>|)>=R<rsup|-1><wide|D|~><around*|(|<wide|x|~>,\<tau\>|)>R>,
  so the transformation of <math|D<around*|(|<wide|k|\<vect\>>|)>> is
  <math|D<around*|(|<wide|k|\<vect\>>|)>=R<rsup|-1><wide|D|~><around*|(|R<wide|k|\<vect\>>|)>R>.

  Now consider the traceless and transverse condition: <math|D<rsub|i i>=0>
  gives <math|<around*|(|D<rsub|i i>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=0>, while
  <math|\<partial\><rsub|i>D<rsub|i j>=0> gives
  <math|k<rsub|i><around*|(|D<rsub|i j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=0>. We
  will quantize k-mode <math|<around*|(|D<rsub|i
  j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>> so the fields <math|D<rsub|i
  j><around*|(|x,\<tau\>|)>>, but for above two constraints there exists only
  two independent variables in <math|<around*|(|D<rsub|i
  j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>>. We need to find them to get a appropriate
  expression of <math|<around*|(|D<rsub|i j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>>.

  Considering a special case would be useful:
  <math|<wide|k|\<vect\>>=<around*|(|0,0,k|)>>, so
  <math|<around*|(|D<rsub|3i>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=0>. Then

  <\equation*>
    <around*|(|D<rsub|i j>|)><rsub|<around*|(|0,0,k|)>>=<around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|h<rsup|+>>|<cell|h<rsup|\<times\>>>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|h<rsup|\<times\>>>|<cell|-h<rsup|+>>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|0>|<cell|0>>>>>|)>,
  </equation*>

  from which we can see that the tensor perturbations have two independent
  degrees.

  It may be noted that we fixed the z-direction to <math|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>,
  but did not restrict the x,y-direction, thus for two coordinates
  <math|<around*|(|x,y,z|)>> and <math|<around*|(|<wide|x|~>,<wide|y|~>,<wide|z|~>=z|)>>
  which are connected by rotating <math|\<theta\>> from
  <math|<around*|{|x|}>> to <math|<around*|{|<wide|x|~>|}>>:
  <math|<around*|(|<wide|x|~>\<mp\>i<wide|y|~>|)>=e<rsup|\<pm\>i\<theta\>><around*|(|x\<mp\>i
  y|)><rsup|>>. One can find that the transformations of
  <math|h<rsup|+,\<times\>>> are: <math|<wide|h|~><rsup|+>\<mp\>i
  <wide|h|~><rsup|\<times\>>=e<rsup|\<pm\>2i\<theta\>><around*|(|h<rsup|+>\<mp\>i
  h<rsup|\<times\>>|)>>, from which one can define:

  <\equation>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|D<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rsup|\<pm\>2><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>>|<cell|=>|<cell|<sqrt|2><around*|(|h<rsup|+>\<mp\>i
    h<rsup|\<times\>>|)>>>|<row|<cell|e<rsup|\<pm\>2><around*|(|<wide|z|^>|)>>|<cell|=>|<cell|<around*|(|<tabular*|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<frac|1|<sqrt|2>>>|<cell|\<pm\><frac|i|<sqrt|2>>>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|\<pm\><frac|i|<sqrt|2>>>|<cell|-<frac|1|<sqrt|2>>>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|0>|<cell|0>>>>>|)>>>>>>;
  </equation>

  then <math|<around*|(|D<rsub|i j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>> can be
  re-expressed as:

  <\equation>
    <around*|(|D<rsub|i j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=<below|<big|sum>|\<sigma\>=\<pm\>2>e<rsub|i
    j><rsup|\<sigma\>><around*|(|<wide|z|^>|)>D<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rsup|\<sigma\>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>,
  </equation>

  where tranformations of <math|D<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rsup|\<pm\>2><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>>
  are: <math|<wide|D|~><rsup|\<pm\>2><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=e<rsup|\<pm\>i2\<theta\>>D<rsup|\<pm\>2><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>>.
  Note that we call the parameter <math|\<sigma\>=\<pm\>2> the <em|helicity>
  of gravitons.

  Now we consider the general direction <math|<wide|<wide|k|\<vect\>>|^>>,
  and hope above eqn still works in a similar way:

  <\equation>
    <label|dijk><around*|(|D<rsub|i j>|)><rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>>=<below|<big|sum>|\<sigma\>=\<pm\>2>e<rsub|i
    j><rsup|\<sigma\>><around*|(|<wide|k|^>|)>D<rsub|<wide|k|\<vect\>>><rsup|\<sigma\>><around*|(|\<tau\>|)>.
  </equation>

  But some subtle thing need to be addressed in the definition of
  <math|e<rsub|i j><rsup|\<sigma\>><around*|(|<wide|k|^>|)>>.

  As we have known the components of <math|D> change when making a coordinate
  transformation <math|<wide|x|~>=R x>: <math|D<around*|(|x,\<tau\>|)>=R<rsup|-1><wide|D|~><around*|(|<wide|x|~>,\<tau\>|)>R>
